	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Making ‘aid for trade’ concrete</h1>

			
			<h4>
												31 May 2009
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>An IDS policy brief on the ‘aid for trade’ debate notes that to date ‘aid for trade’ initiatives ‘have often not been translated into a set of clear and concrete actions’. Rather they have focused on establishing ‘the right institutional framework’. While the importance of this initial step is recognised it is now felt to be essential to translate policy frameworks into concrete actions. It is argued that in addition more attention should be paid to the particular industrial and agricultural policy instruments which should be set in place.</p><p>More specifically the brief points out that the ‘constraints preventing local producers from entering global value chains or outsourcing contracts are sometimes very specific and different from general constraints on exports. Policy responses should therefore also be distinct’. The report calls for:</p>
<ul>

<li>‘more solid diagnosis of the supply constraints that affect specific developing countries and/or sectors’;</li>

<li>‘placing more focus on demand factors and connecting local producers to growing markets’;</li>

<li>investing in more solid research, for example, by analysing who and how to assist in directing trade-adjustment assistance’;</li>

<li>‘assessing the impact of low-carbon growth measures on developing-country exports and integrating these with “aid for trade” strategies’.</li>

</ul>
<p>Complementary to this analysis CTA and ECDPM organised in 2008 two dialogue meetings on Aid for Trade and Agriculture, one focusing on All ACP countries and the other on the Caribbean region, which led to two reports including recommendations for the deployment of Aid for Trade in the agricultural sector.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
